gers were passive participants in the process, the author shows that they actually played a crucial role in the subdivision of communal property. Papantla's story is at odds with prevailing stereotypes of pueblo history, and thus points to the need for a broad reexamination of the causes, process, and consequences of rural social change in pre-revolutionary Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361881740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503618817423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503618817/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles